icted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  ain recent years, there has been a growing interest in the legal aspects of mass torts in Europe. Both academics, legislatures, courts and policymakers throughout the whole of Europe have been struggling with the challenges that such ‚massification‘ of private law relationships poses both in and outside of tort law. The subject moves between the law of civil procedure, substantive tort law, access to justice debates and regulatory frameworks for mass disputes. This volume offers both a caleidoscopic review of real-life key cases of mass tort and an in-depth reflection on the broader implications of mass tort in Europe. Thus, the challenges posed by mass torts are explored, mapped and analysed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aClass actions (Civil procedure)zEuropevCases. 0aClass actions (Civil procedure)zEurope. 0aTortszEuropevCases. 0aTortszEurope. 4aSchadenersatzrecht. 7aLAW / Torts.2bisacsh  aTort Law.1 aBoldon, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoom, Willem H. van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoom, Willem H. van, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrinkmann, Moritz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiaves, Filippo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoggiola, Nadia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerrari, Melissa R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraziadei, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodges, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoch, Bernhard A., econtributor.